# Download Watcher

A local dashboard for long-running downloads, model pulls, backups, and file transfers. Progress bar, speed, ETA, file notifications, stall detection, and audio alarms — all from a browser tab, no cloud, no account needed.

![Download Watcher dashboard](dl-hero.png)

---

## Why this exists

Every time I pull a large model, grab a Linux ISO, or run an overnight backup, I'd find myself checking a terminal every few minutes, wondering if it was still alive. Hard to tell stalls from slow transfers. No alert when something fails hours in. I wanted a tool that sits open in a tab, shows real progress, and speaks up when something goes wrong.

So I built this.

## What it does

| What | How |
|---|---|
| **Progress bar** | Animated fill with file count overlay |
| **Transfer speed** | MB/s calculated from byte deltas |
| **Estimated time** | Live estimate based on current rate |
| **File notifications** | Pops up when each file lands |
| **Milestone alerts** | Notifies at every 10% |
| **Stall detection** | Flags if nothing changes for 5+ minutes |
| **Failure alarm** | Audible alert through speakers when download stops |
| **Browser backup alarm** | Web Audio siren in the dashboard tab |
| **Heartbeat** | Soft chirp every ~30s so you know it's alive, with mute toggle |
| **Density map** | Visual grid of all files so you can see patterns |

## Works with anything

- Hugging Face model pulls (`hf download ...`)
- `rsync` over SSH
- `wget` / `curl` large files
- `git lfs pull`
- Docker image pulls (wrapped in systemd)
- Any process you can watch by file count or byte growth
- Any directory where files land one by one

## Quick start

```bash
# One-time setup
bash watcher/dl-setup.sh
# → enter download directory, file count, systemd service name

# Launch (or click the app icon)
bash watcher/dl-launcher.sh
# → opens http://localhost:18999 in your browser
```

To pin to taskbar: search "Download Watcher" in your app menu → right-click → Add to Favorites.

## Requirements

- Linux with PulseAudio (for audio alerts)
- Python 3 (ships with every distro)
- `jq` (for the monitor script — `apt install jq`)
- `systemctl --user` if you want service monitoring
- A browser for the dashboard

No npm, no Docker, no API keys, no cloud.

For your next download, run `dl-setup.sh` with the new target and click the app icon.

---

Made to scratch my own itch. Hope it helps scratch yours.